3.4 Modeling Pipeline without Neural Networks¶

Modeling Approach

To effectively predict loan default risk, we implemented a structured modeling process that evaluated multiple machine learning algorithms, explored feature selection techniques, and conducted hyperparameter tuning. Below, we outline our methodology and findings, including descriptions of the models and the metrics used for evaluation.

Modeling Process

  1. Feature Engineering and Final Dataset Creation:

    • Feature Engineering: Based on insights from Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and business understanding, we engineered new features to enhance predictive power.
    • Dataset Aggregation: Aggregated features from secondary datasets using custom functions designed to summarize information effectively.
    • Pipeline Creation: Developed a pipeline for categorical and numerical features. Categorical features were encoded, and numerical features were aggregated using statistical functions such as mean, sum, and max.
    • Dataset Merging: Merged all secondary datasets with the primary application dataset using a left join on SK_ID_CURR. Each merge added new aggregated features to the dataset, resulting in a comprehensive and unified dataset.
    • Data Transformation: Handled missing and infinite values by replacin [np.inf, -np.inf] with np.nan.
    • Split the dataset into X_train, X_test, and X_valid.
    • Label Assignment: The target variable (y_train) was assigned as the TARGET column from X_train.

  1. Baseline Model: Logistic Regression was chosen as a baseline due to its simplicity, interpretability, and effectiveness for binary classification tasks.

  2. Full Feature Set Models: Initial experiments included running Logistic Regression, Decision Trees, Random Forests, Gradient Boosting, XGBoost, and LightGBM on all 208 features.

  3. Feature Selection: To reduce dimensionality and improve interpretability, we employed:

    • Correlation analysis to remove highly correlated features.
    • Feature importance scores from Decision Trees and Random Forests.
    • Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to retain components explaining 95% of variance.

    This process reduced the dataset to 20 features, which were used in subsequent experiments.

  4. Reduced Feature Set Models: The same models were re-trained on the reduced dataset, including Support Vector Machines (SVC) due to its efficiency with fewer features.

  5. Ensemble Models:

    • A voting classifier (soft voting) averaged class probabilities across models.
    • A stacking classifier used predictions from all models as input features to a meta-model.

  6. Hyperparameter Tuning: Focused on XGBoost, our best-performing model, using the reduced feature set. Parameters tuned included:

    • learning_rate
    • max_depth
    • subsample
    • colsample_bytree

  7. Performance Metrics: We evaluated models using Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1 Score, AUC-ROC, and Log Loss to capture different aspects of performance.

Model Description

These models were selected for their suitability for binary classification tasks and ability to handle large, diverse datasets with a mix of categorical and numerical features.

Algorithm Implementation Loss Function
Logistic Regression sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression Log Loss (Binary Cross-Entropy)
Decision Tree Classifier sklearn.tree.DecisionTreeClassifier Gini Impurity / Entropy
Random Forest sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier Gini Impurity / Entropy
Support Vector Machine sklearn.svm.SVC Hinge Loss (SVM Loss)
Gradient Boosting sklearn.ensemble.GradientBoostingClassifier Log Loss (Binary Cross-Entropy)
Extreme Gradient Boosting xgboost.XGBClassifier Log Loss (Binary Cross-Entropy)
Light Gradient Boosting lightgbm.LGBMClassifier Log Loss (Binary Cross-Entropy)
Voting Classifier sklearn.ensemble.VotingClassifier Weighted Average of Component Losses
Stacking Classifier sklearn.ensemble.StackingClassifier Meta-Model Loss
  • Logistic Regression: A straightforward and interpretable model for binary classification, used as a baseline to evaluate the performance of more advanced models.
  • Decision Tree Classifier: Creates interpretable decision pathways by splitting on features. Helps understand which specific features indicate repayment likelihood.
  • Random Forest: An ensemble of decision trees, offering robustness to overfitting and capturing complex, non-linear feature interactions.
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM): Finds the optimal hyperplane for class separation, making it effective for high-dimensional feature spaces.
  • Gradient Boosting: Sequentially builds models to correct the errors of prior models. Effective for structured data with complex, non-linear relationships.
  • Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost): An optimized version of gradient boosting with advanced features like regularization, missing value handling, and parallel processing for scalability.
  • Light Gradient Boosting (LightGBM): Designed for speed and memory efficiency, handles large datasets and high-cardinality categorical features while being robust to overfitting.
  • Voting Classifier: Combines predictions from multiple models using a soft voting strategy, leveraging the strengths of each model for improved performance.
  • Stacking Classifier: Uses a meta-model to combine the outputs of several base models, often leading to better generalization by exploiting model complementarities.

Model Evaluation

To evaluate our models for the HCDR dataset, we are using accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score, AUC-ROC, and log loss metrics, which are common metrics used to evaluate classification models. The table below contains a description and formula for each metric.

Name Description Formula
Accuracy Proportion of correctly predicted samples out of the total samples $$\text{Accuracy} = \frac{\text{True Positives + True Negatives}}{\text{True Positives + True Negatives + False Positives + False Negatives}}$$
Precision Proportion of true positive predictions out of all positive predictions $$\text{Precision} = \frac{\text{True Positives}}{\text{True Positives} + \text{False Positives}}$$
Recall (Sensitivity) Proportion of actual positives correctly identified $$\text{Recall} = \frac{\text{True Positives}}{\text{True Positives} + \text{False Negatives}}$$
F1 Score Harmonic mean of precision and recall, balancing the two metrics $$\text{F1 Score} = 2 \cdot \frac{\text{Precision} \times \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision} + \text{Recall}}$$
AUC-ROC Area under the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve, measuring model's ability to distinguish between classes $$\text{AUC-ROC} = \int \text{ROC Curve}$$
Log Loss Logarithmic loss penalizes wrong predictions more as they deviate from true class probabilities $$\text{Log Loss} = -\frac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^{m} \sum_{k=1}^{K} y_k^{(i)} \log(\hat{p}_k^{(i)})$$

  • Accuracy is the proportion of correctly predicted values divided by the total number of predicted values. It basically measures how often a machine learning model correctly predicts the outcome. This metric doesn't work well if the data set is imbalanced, meaning the overwhelming majority of the Target variables have the same classification.

  • Precision is the proportion of true positive values predicted to the total number of positive values predicted. For projects where false positives are less desirable, precision is a good metric choice to minimize them.

  • Recall is the proportion of true positive values predicted to the total number of the true positives and the total number of the false negatives. For projects where false negatives are less desirable, recall is a good metric choice.

  • F1 Score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall. For projects where both false positives and false negatives are similarly weighted then F1 is a good metric choice.

  • AUC-ROC is Area under the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve which measures a model's ability to distinguish between classes. AUC-ROC is a good metric choice for projects with highly imbalanced data sets.

  • Log (Logarithmic) loss penalizes wrong predictions more as they deviate from true class probabilities. Log loss is a good metric choice for balanced and imbalanced data sets but can be sensitive to outliers.

3.4.1. Feature Engineering and Dataset Aggregation¶

In this project, aggregation was a critical step because many of the datasets were provided at a level that did not align with the unique identifier of the loan applications (SK_ID_CURR). For example, data such as installment payments, credit card balances, and POS loans contained multiple entries, representing either monthly snapshots or transaction records. This misalignment required us to summarize these datasets at the SK_ID_CURR level to effectively integrate them into the primary dataset and make them usable for predictive modeling. Additionally, new features were engineered during aggregation.

The prevAppsFeaturesAggregater function handled the previous_application dataset, which included historical loan applications with multiple rows per client. Aggregation was performed using statistical functions such as min, max, and mean on numeric features like AMT_APPLICATION and AMT_ANNUITY. A new feature, range_AMT_APPLICATION, was created to represent the variability in requested loan amounts. This variability is meaningful for predicting whether a client is likely to repay because it provides insight into the consistency or fluctuation in their financial needs over time.

The BureauFeaturesAggregater function processed the bureau dataset, which contained records of clients previous credits with other institutions. It included features such as AMT_CREDIT_SUM and AMT_CREDIT_SUM_OVERDUE. A new feature, OVERDUE_CREDIT_RATIO, was created to represent the ratio of overdue credit to the total credit. This ratio is a key indicator of financial risk, as a high value suggests difficulty in managing credit obligations. Missing values in the overdue amounts were handled during aggregation.

The CreditCardBalanceFeatureEngineer and CreditCardBalanceAggregator functions worked on the credit_card_balance dataset, which contained monthly records for clients credit cards. These functions created features like CREDIT_UTIL_RATIO, the ratio of balance to credit limit, and DPD_MAX, the maximum days past due across months. Missing values were also handled.

The InstallmentsFeaturesAggregater function aggregated data from the installments_payments dataset, which detailed individual loan installment records. It created features such as payment_delay_days (difference between scheduled and actual payment dates) and payment_to_installment_ratio (proportion of payment made relative to the installment amount). Aggregating these features allows the model to capture repayment patterns over time, such as chronic late payments or consistent shortfalls in payment amounts. Missing values in the payment data were replaced with expected values to reflect on-time payments when no delays were recorded.

The POSCashBalanceFeaturesAggregater function aggregated the POS_CASH_balance dataset, which tracked the status of POS and cash loans. This dataset included fields such as SK_DPD (days past due) and CNT_INSTALMENT_FUTURE (remaining installments). New features, like POS_REMAINING_INSTALMENTS_RATIO, which calculated the ratio of remaining installments to total installments, were engineered to highlight repayment progress.

# Create aggregate features (via pipeline)
class prevAppsFeaturesAggregater(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, features=None): # no *args or **kargs
        self.features = features
        self.agg_op_features = {}
        for f in features:
            #self.agg_op_features[f] = {f"{f}_{func}":func for func in ["min", "max", "mean"]}
            self.agg_op_features[f] = ['min', 'max', 'mean']

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        #from IPython.core.debugger import Pdb as pdb;    pdb().set_trace() #breakpoint; dont forget to quit
        result = X.groupby(["SK_ID_CURR"]).agg(self.agg_op_features)
        result.columns = ['_'.join(col).strip() for col in result.columns]
        #result.columns = result.columns.droplevel()
        result = result.reset_index(level=["SK_ID_CURR"])
        result['range_AMT_APPLICATION'] = result['AMT_APPLICATION_max'] - result['AMT_APPLICATION_min']
        return result # return dataframe with the join key "SK_ID_CURR"


from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
def test_driver_prevAppsFeaturesAggregater(df, features):
    print(f"df.shape: {df.shape}\n")
    print(f"df[{features}][0:5]: \n{df[features][0:5]}")
    test_pipeline = make_pipeline(prevAppsFeaturesAggregater(features))
    return(test_pipeline.fit_transform(df))

features = ['AMT_ANNUITY', 'AMT_APPLICATION']
features = ['AMT_ANNUITY',

ds_name = 'bureau'
datasets[ds_name] = load_data(os.path.join(DATA_DIR, f'{ds_name}.csv'), ds_name)
bureau = datasets['bureau']
bureau_features = ['AMT_CREDIT_SUM', 'AMT_CREDIT_SUM_DEBT', 'AMT_CREDIT_SUM_LIMIT','AMT_CREDIT_SUM_OVERDUE', 'AMT_ANNUITY']
class BureauFeaturesAggregater(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, features=None):
      self.features = features
      self.agg_op_features = {}
      for f in features:
        self.agg_op_features[f] = ['min', 'max', 'mean']

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
      return self


    def transform(self, X, y=None):
    # Create overdue credit ratio
      sum_overdue_credit = X.groupby('SK_ID_CURR')['AMT_CREDIT_SUM_OVERDUE'].sum()
      sum_total_credit = X.groupby('SK_ID_CURR')['AMT_CREDIT_SUM'].sum()
      overdue_credit_ratio = sum_overdue_credit/sum_total_credit

      result = X.groupby('SK_ID_CURR').agg(self.agg_op_features)
      result.columns = ['_'.join(col).strip() for col in result.columns]

      result['OVERDUE_CREDIT_RATIO'] = overdue_credit_ratio

      return result


from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
def test_driver_BureauFeaturesAggregater(df, features):
    print(f"df.shape: {df.shape}\n")
    print(f"df[{features}][0:5]: \n{df[features][0:5]}")
    test_pipeline = make_pipeline(BureauFeaturesAggregater(features))
    return(test_pipeline.fit_transform(df))

class BureauBalanceFeaturesAggregater(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, features=None):
      self.features = features
      self.agg_op_features = {}
      for f in features:
        self.agg_op_features[f] = ['count']

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
      return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
    # Get counts of each loan status (Active, closed, days past due, etc.) in bureau balance table
      result = X.groupby(['SK_ID_CURR', 'STATUS']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)
      result.columns = [f'STATUS_{col}_COUNT' for col in result.columns]
      result = result.reset_index(level=['SK_ID_CURR'])
      result.fillna(0, inplace=True)
      result['SK_ID_CURR'] = result['SK_ID_CURR'].astype(int)
      return result

# Test the BureauBalanceFeaturesAggregater
def test_driver_BureauBalanceFeaturesAggregater(df, features):
    print(f"df.shape: {df.shape}\n")
    print(f"df[{features}][0:5]: \n{df[features][0:5]}")
    test_pipeline = make_pipeline(BureauBalanceFeaturesAggregater(features))
    return(test_pipeline.fit_transform(df))

ds_name = 'credit_card_balance'
datasets[ds_name] = load_data(os.path.join(DATA_DIR, f'{ds_name}.csv'), ds_name)
ccb = datasets['credit_card_balance']
ccb_features = ['AMT_BALANCE', 'AMT_CREDIT_LIMIT_ACTUAL', 'AMT_DRAWINGS_CURRENT', # Reduced number of features
               'AMT_PAYMENT_TOTAL_CURRENT', 'CNT_DRAWINGS_CURRENT', 'CNT_DRAWINGS_ATM_CURRENT' ]

class CreditCardFeaturesAggregater(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, features=None):
      self.features = features
      self.agg_op_features = {}
      for f in features:
        self.agg_op_features[f] = ['min', 'max', 'mean'] # Modified from 'sum' to 'min'

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
      return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
    # Handle missing values for the numerical features by filling with zeros
        X = X.fillna(0)

    # Create new features
        credit_util_ratio = X['AMT_BALANCE'] / X['AMT_CREDIT_LIMIT_ACTUAL']
        payment_draw_ratio = X['AMT_PAYMENT_TOTAL_CURRENT'] / X['AMT_DRAWINGS_CURRENT']
        amt_drawings_total = X['AMT_DRAWINGS_CURRENT'] + X['AMT_DRAWINGS_OTHER_CURRENT'] + X['AMT_DRAWINGS_POS_CURRENT']
        cnt_drawings_total = X['CNT_DRAWINGS_CURRENT'] + X['CNT_DRAWINGS_ATM_CURRENT'] + X['CNT_DRAWINGS_OTHER_CURRENT']
        dpd_max = X[['SK_DPD', 'SK_DPD_DEF']].max(axis=1)

    # Aggregate features at SK_ID_CURR level
        result = X.groupby('SK_ID_CURR').agg(self.agg_op_features)
        result.columns = ['_'.join(col).strip() for col in result.columns]

    # Add the newly calculated features to the aggregated result
        result['CREDIT_UTIL_RATIO'] = credit_util_ratio.groupby(X['SK_ID_CURR']).mean()
        result['PAYMENT_DRAW_RATIO'] = payment_draw_ratio.groupby(X['SK_ID_CURR']).mean()
        result['AMT_DRAWINGS_TOTAL'] = amt_drawings_total.groupby(X['SK_ID_CURR']).mean()
        result['CNT_DRAWINGS_TOTAL'] = cnt_drawings_total.groupby(X['SK_ID_CURR']).mean()
        result['DPD_MAX'] = dpd_max.groupby(X['SK_ID_CURR']).max()

        return result


from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
def test_driver_CreditCardFeaturesAggregater(df, features):
    print(f"df.shape: {df.shape}\n")
    print(f"df[{features}][0:5]: \n{df[features][0:5]}")
    test_pipeline = make_pipeline(CreditCardFeaturesAggregater(features))
    return(test_pipeline.fit_transform(df))

class InstallmentsFeaturesAggregater(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self):
        self.delay_agg_op = {
            'payment_delay_days': ['mean', 'max']  # Include average_delay and max_delay
        }
        self.payment_agg_op = {
            'amt_payment_difference': ['sum', 'std'],  # Include total_payment_difference and variability_payment_difference
            'payment_to_installment_ratio': ['mean', 'max']  # Include average_payment_ratio and max_payment_ratio
        }

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):

        # Create new features
        X['payment_delay_days'] = X['DAYS_ENTRY_PAYMENT'] - X['DAYS_INSTALMENT']
        X['amt_payment_difference'] = X['AMT_INSTALMENT'] - X['AMT_PAYMENT']
        X['payment_to_installment_ratio'] = X['AMT_PAYMENT'] / X['AMT_INSTALMENT']

        # Aggregate delay features
        delay_features = X.groupby('SK_ID_CURR').agg(self.delay_agg_op)
        delay_features.columns = ['_'.join(col).strip() for col in delay_features.columns]

        # Aggregate payment features
        payment_features = X.groupby('SK_ID_CURR').agg(self.payment_agg_op)
        payment_features.columns = ['_'.join(col).strip() for col in payment_features.columns]

        # Combine both aggregated features
        aggregated_features = pd.concat([delay_features, payment_features], axis=1)

        return aggregated_features.reset_index()

# Test function for the updated InstallmentsFeaturesAggregater
def test_driver_InstallmentsFeaturesAggregater(df):
    print(f"df.shape: {df.shape}\n")
    print(f"Sample df columns: {df.columns}")
    test_pipeline = make_pipeline(InstallmentsFeaturesAggregater())
    result = test_pipeline.fit_transform(df)
    return result

class POSCashBalanceFeaturesAggregater(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self):
        self.numerical_agg_op = {
            'SK_DPD_DEF': ['max', 'mean', 'min'],  # Delays with a legal default
            'SK_DPD': ['max', 'mean', 'min'],      # Days past due
            'MONTHS_BALANCE': ['max', 'mean', 'size'],  # Tracking loan duration
            'CNT_INSTALMENT': ['max', 'size'],     # Total installments
            'CNT_INSTALMENT_FUTURE': ['max', 'size', 'sum']  # Remaining installments
        }
        self.categorical_agg_op = {}  # Placeholder for one-hot-encoded columns

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
      # One-hot encode `NAME_CONTRACT_STATUS`
      one_hot = pd.get_dummies(X['NAME_CONTRACT_STATUS'], prefix='NAME_CONTRACT_STATUS')
      X = pd.concat([X, one_hot], axis=1)

      # Add one-hot encoded columns to categorical aggregations
      for col in one_hot.columns:
          self.categorical_agg_op[col] = ['mean']

      # Aggregate numerical features at SK_ID_CURR level
      numerical_agg = X.groupby('SK_ID_CURR').agg(self.numerical_agg_op)
      numerical_agg.columns = ['POS_' + '_'.join(col).upper() for col in numerical_agg.columns]

      # Aggregate categorical features at SK_ID_CURR level
      categorical_agg = X.groupby('SK_ID_CURR').agg(self.categorical_agg_op)
      categorical_agg.columns = ['POS_' + '_'.join(col).upper() for col in categorical_agg.columns]

      # Combine numerical and categorical features
      aggregated_features = pd.concat([numerical_agg, categorical_agg], axis=1)

      # Reset index to make 'SK_ID_CURR' a column
      aggregated_features = aggregated_features.reset_index()

      # Loan-level features (SK_ID_PREV level)
      X_sorted = X.sort_values(by=['SK_ID_PREV', 'MONTHS_BALANCE'])
      pos_group = X_sorted.groupby('SK_ID_PREV')

      loan_level_features = pd.DataFrame()
      loan_level_features['SK_ID_CURR'] = pos_group['SK_ID_CURR'].first()
      loan_level_features['POS_LOAN_COMPLETED_MEAN'] = pos_group['NAME_CONTRACT_STATUS_Completed'].mean()
      loan_level_features['POS_COMPLETED_BEFORE_MEAN'] = (
          pos_group['CNT_INSTALMENT'].first() - pos_group['CNT_INSTALMENT'].last()
      )
      loan_level_features['POS_COMPLETED_BEFORE_MEAN'] = loan_level_features.apply(
          lambda x: 1 if x['POS_COMPLETED_BEFORE_MEAN'] > 0 and x['POS_LOAN_COMPLETED_MEAN'] > 0 else 0, axis=1
      )
      loan_level_features['POS_REMAINING_INSTALMENTS'] = pos_group['CNT_INSTALMENT_FUTURE'].last()
      loan_level_features['POS_REMAINING_INSTALMENTS_RATIO'] = (
          pos_group['CNT_INSTALMENT_FUTURE'].last() / pos_group['CNT_INSTALMENT'].last()
      ).fillna(0)  # Handle potential division by zero

      # Aggregate loan-level features to SK_ID_CURR level
      loan_level_agg = loan_level_features.groupby('SK_ID_CURR').sum().reset_index()

      # Merge aggregated features with loan-level features
      final_agg = pd.merge(aggregated_features, loan_level_agg, on='SK_ID_CURR', how='left')

      return final_agg

# Test function for the updated POSCashBalanceFeaturesAggregater
def test_driver_POSCashBalanceFeaturesAggregater(df):
    print(f"df.shape: {df.shape}\n")
    print(f"Sample df columns: {df.columns}")
    test_pipeline = make_pipeline(POSCashBalanceFeaturesAggregater())
    result = test_pipeline.fit_transform(df)
    return result

3.4.2 Application test/train Augmentation¶

We used the aggregater functions we created to build a pipeline for each of these data sets. We merged the datasets sequentially into the primary application dataset using a left join on SK_ID_CURR. Each merge operation appended the aggregated features from the secondary dataset to the primary dataset.

# Initialize pipelines for each dataset
bureau_feature_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('bureau_aggregater', BureauFeaturesAggregater(bureau_features))
])

bureau_balance_feature_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('bureau_balance_aggregater', BureauBalanceFeaturesAggregater(features=bureau_balance_features))
])

credit_card_feature_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('credit_card_aggregater', CreditCardFeaturesAggregater(features=ccb_features))
])

installments_feature_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('installments_aggregater', InstallmentsFeaturesAggregater())
])

pos_cash_feature_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('pos_cash_aggregater', POSCashBalanceFeaturesAggregater())
])

prev_apps_feature_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('prev_apps_aggregater', prevAppsFeaturesAggregater(features))
])

# Example datasets
X_train = datasets['application_train']  # Primary dataset
bureau = datasets['bureau']
ID_combos = bureau[['SK_ID_CURR','SK_ID_BUREAU']].drop_duplicates()
bureau_balance = pd.merge(datasets['bureau_balance'], ID_combos, on='SK_ID_BUREAU', how='left')
credit_card_balance = datasets['credit_card_balance']
installments = datasets['installments_payments']
pos_cash = datasets['POS_CASH_balance']
previous_apps = datasets['previous_application']

merge_all_data = True

if merge_all_data:
    # 1. Transform and merge Bureau/Bureau Balance data
    bureau_aggregated = bureau_feature_pipeline.transform(bureau)
    X_train = X_train.merge(bureau_aggregated, how='left', on='SK_ID_CURR')
    bureau_balance_aggregated = bureau_balance_feature_pipeline.transform(bureau_balance)
    X_train = X_train.merge(bureau_balance_aggregated, how='left', on='SK_ID_CURR')

    # 2. Transform and merge Credit Card Balance data
    credit_card_aggregated = credit_card_feature_pipeline.transform(credit_card_balance)
    X_train = X_train.merge(credit_card_aggregated, how='left', on='SK_ID_CURR')

    # 3. Transform and merge Installments data
    installments_aggregated = installments_feature_pipeline.transform(installments)
    X_train = X_train.merge(installments_aggregated, how='left', on='SK_ID_CURR')

    # 4. Transform and merge POS Cash Balance data
    pos_cash_aggregated = pos_cash_feature_pipeline.transform(pos_cash)
    X_train = X_train.merge(pos_cash_aggregated, how='left', on='SK_ID_CURR')

    # 5. Transform and merge Previous Applications data
    previous_apps_aggregated = prev_apps_feature_pipeline.transform(previous_apps)
    X_train = X_train.merge(previous_apps_aggregated, how='left', on='SK_ID_CURR')

# Print resulting dataset shape and columns for verification
print(f"Transformed X_train shape: {X_train.shape}")
print(f"Columns in transformed X_train: {X_train.columns}")

3.4.5 Model testing - no hyper parameter tuning (pre-Feature Selection)¶

After successfully testing our baseline model, we built used GridSearchCV to train using 6 different algorithms with their default parameters: LogisticsRegression, DecisionTree, RandomForest, Gradient Boosting, XG Boosting, and Light Gradient Boosting. Due to processing limitations we will not be training the Support Vector Machines Classifier. We trained this model later after feature selection.

        ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
        ('model', model)

def populate_expLog(X_train, X_valid, X_test, model_nameti, model):
  exp_name = f"{model_name}_{X_train.shape[1]}_features"
  from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, log_loss
  global expLog
  expLog.loc[len(expLog)] = [f"{exp_name}"] + list(np.round(
                [accuracy_score(y_train, model.predict(X_train)),
                  accuracy_score(y_valid, model.predict(X_valid)),
                  accuracy_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test)),
                  roc_auc_score(y_train, model.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]),
                  roc_auc_score(y_valid, model.predict_proba(X_valid)[:, 1]),
                  roc_auc_score(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]),
                  precision_score(y_train, model.predict(X_train)),
                  precision_score(y_valid, model.predict(X_valid)),
                  precision_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test)),
                  recall_score(y_train, model.predict(X_train)),
                  recall_score(y_valid, model.predict(X_valid)),
                  recall_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test)),
                  f1_score(y_train, model.predict(X_train)),
                  f1_score(y_valid, model.predict(X_valid)),
                  f1_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test)),
                  log_loss(y_train, model.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]),
                  log_loss(y_valid, model.predict_proba(X_valid)[:, 1]),
                  log_loss(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])],
                4))

3.4.6 Feature Selection¶

To improve model performance and interpretability, we combined correlation analysis, feature importance ranking, and Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to select the most relevant features.

First, correlation analysis identified highly correlated feature pairs (correlation > 0.9), where only one feature from each pair was retained to reduce multicollinearity. Next, feature importance was computed using Decision Trees and Random Forests, with scores averaged to prioritize impactful features. Correlated features were resolved by retaining the one with the higher importance score.

Finally, PCA was applied to the reduced dataset, retaining components that explained 95% of the variance.

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
def perform_pca_analysis(X, n_components=0.95):
    """
    Perform PCA analysis with missing value imputation, plot key PCA graphs,
    and suggest a good cutoff point for the number of principal components.
    """
    # Handle missing values
    imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
    X_imputed = imputer.fit_transform(X)

    # Standardize the data
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_imputed)

    # Fit PCA with n_components=0.95 to retain 95% of variance
    pca = PCA(n_components=n_components, svd_solver='full', random_state=42)
    X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

    # Step 4: Explained variance analysis
    explained_variance_ratio = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
    cumulative_variance = np.cumsum(explained_variance_ratio)

    # Print suggested cutoff point
    cutoff_point = np.argmax(cumulative_variance >= n_components) + 1
    print(f"Suggested number of components to retain {n_components*100:.0f}% variance: {cutoff_point}")

    # Bar plot of explained variance by each component (Scree Plot)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.bar(range(1, len(explained_variance_ratio) + 1), explained_variance_ratio, alpha=0.7, align='center', label='Individual Explained Variance')
    plt.xlabel('Principal Component Index')
    plt.ylabel('Explained Variance Ratio')
    plt.title('Scree Plot: Variance Explained by PCA Components')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

    # Cumulative variance explained plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.plot(range(1, len(cumulative_variance) + 1), cumulative_variance, marker='o', label='Cumulative Variance Explained')
    plt.axhline(y=n_components, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'{n_components*100:.0f}% Variance Explained Threshold')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Components')
    plt.ylabel('Cumulative Variance')
    plt.title('Cumulative Variance Explained by PCA Components')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()

    # Pairplot of first 3 PCA components
    if X_pca.shape[1] >= 3:
        pca_df = pd.DataFrame(X_pca[:, :3], columns=['PC1', 'PC2', 'PC3'])
        sns.pairplot(pca_df)
        plt.suptitle('Pairplot of First Three Principal Components', y=1.02)
        plt.show()

    return pca, X_pca

# Check if PCA was performed and if explained_variance_ratio_ is accessible
if hasattr(pca, "explained_variance_ratio_"):
    total_variance_explained = 0
    n_top_components = 12  # Customize the number of components to analyze

    print("\nIndividual Variance Contributions for Top Components:")
    print("-----------------------------------------------------")
    for j in range(min(n_top_components, len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))):  # Safeguard against index errors
        contribution = pca.explained_variance_ratio_[j]
        print(f"Principal Component {j+1}: {contribution:.4f} ({contribution*100:.2f}%)")
        total_variance_explained += contribution

    print(f"\nTotal Explained Variance by Top {n_top_components} Components: {total_variance_explained:.4f} ({total_variance_explained*100:.2f}%)")
else:
    print("PCA failed or explained_variance_ratio_ is not available.")

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
# Correlation Analysis
def correlation_analysis(X, correlation_threshold=0.9):
    """
    Identify pairs of highly correlated features and return the features to drop.
    """
    correlation_matrix = X.corr()

    # Identify highly correlated pairs
    correlated_features = set()
    for i in range(len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
        for j in range(i):
            if abs(correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > correlation_threshold:
                colname1 = correlation_matrix.columns[i]
                colname2 = correlation_matrix.columns[j]
                correlated_features.add((colname1, colname2))

    print(f"Highly correlated feature pairs (|correlation| > {correlation_threshold}):")
    for pair in correlated_features:
        print(pair)

    return correlated_features

# Feature Importance
def compute_feature_importance(X_train, y_train, preprocessor):
    """
    Compute feature importance using Decision Tree and Random Forest models.
    """
    # Decision Tree
    dt_model = Pipeline([
        ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
        ('decision_tree', DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42))
    ])
    dt_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    dt_importances = dt_model.named_steps['decision_tree'].feature_importances_

    # Random Forest
    rf_model = Pipeline([
        ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
        ('random_forest', RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42))
    ])
    rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    rf_importances = rf_model.named_steps['random_forest'].feature_importances_

    # Extract feature names
    preprocessed_features = preprocessor.get_feature_names_out().tolist()

    # Ensure lengths match
    if len(preprocessed_features) != len(dt_importances):
        raise ValueError("Mismatch between preprocessed features and importance values.")

    # Combine Results
    importance_df = pd.DataFrame({
        'Feature': preprocessed_features,
        'DT_Importance': dt_importances,
        'RF_Importance': rf_importances
    })
    importance_df['Average_Importance'] = importance_df[['DT_Importance', 'RF_Importance']].mean(axis=1)
    importance_df.sort_values(by='Average_Importance', ascending=False, inplace=True)

    return importance_df

# Combine Correlation and Feature Importance
def combine_correlation_and_importance(correlated_features, importance_df):
    """
    For each correlated pair, retain the feature with higher average importance.
    """
    features_to_drop = set()
    for col1, col2 in correlated_features:
        avg_importance_col1 = importance_df.loc[importance_df['Feature'] == col1, 'Average_Importance'].values
        avg_importance_col2 = importance_df.loc[importance_df['Feature'] == col2, 'Average_Importance'].values

        if len(avg_importance_col1) > 0 and len(avg_importance_col2) > 0:
            if avg_importance_col1[0] < avg_importance_col2[0]:
                features_to_drop.add(col1)
            else:
                features_to_drop.add(col2)

    return features_to_drop

# Feature Selection
def select_final_features(importance_df, features_to_drop, top_features_cutoff=20):
    """
    Combine results of correlation analysis and feature importance to select features.
    """
    top_features = set(importance_df['Feature'].head(top_features_cutoff))
    final_features = top_features - features_to_drop
    return final_features

# Reapply PCA
def reapply_pca(X_train_reduced):
    """
    Perform PCA on the reduced dataset.
    """
    from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train_reduced)

    pca = PCA(n_components=0.95, svd_solver='full', random_state=42)
    X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

    print(f"PCA explained variance ratio: {pca.explained_variance_ratio_}")
    print(f"Number of components to retain 95% variance: {pca.n_components_}")
    return X_pca, pca

# Reuse PCA from previous analysis
pca_n_components = pca.n_components_

# Add PCA to numerical transformer
numerical_transformer_pca = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')),
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('pca', PCA(n_components=pca_n_components))
])

categorical_transformer_encoded = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('onehot', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))  # OneHotEncode categorical features
])

# Updated preprocessor
preprocessor_pca = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numerical_transformer_pca, numerical_features),  # Apply PCA to numerical features
        ('cat', categorical_transformer_encoded, categorical_features)  # Encode categorical features
    ]
)

# Define models
pca_models = {
    "LogisticRegression": LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
}

# Create pipelines with PCA preprocessing
pca_pipelines = {}
for model_name, model in pca_models.items():
    pca_pipelines[model_name] = Pipeline(steps=[
        ('preprocessor', preprocessor_pca),
        ('model', model)
    ])

We conducted an analysis of Logistic Regression with PCA applied to both the full feature set and a reduced set of 20 selected features to evaluate its impact on model performance. When PCA was applied to the full feature set, the model achieved an accuracy of 91.60%, with a macro F1-score of 0.49 and poor recall for the minority class (2%). Similarly, when PCA was applied to only the 20 selected features, the accuracy slightly dropped to 91.58%, with no significant improvement in the macro F1-score or recall. These results indicate that reducing dimensionality using PCA, even with fewer features, did not improve the models ability to generalize or address the severe class imbalance. Additionally, training with PCA on the reduced set was computationally more expensive due to the overhead of the PCA transformation. This suggests that addressing class imbalance directly would likely yield greater performance improvements than applying PCA.

Despite these initial findings, we will explored the reduced feature set across all our experiments to determine if the observed trends hold consistent or if the reduced features provide advantages in other modeling scenarios.

3.4.7 Ensemble Models on Full Dataset¶

We trained 2 ensemble models using all of our models above. First, we trained a voting classifier, in this case a soft voting classifier which uses the probability of each class for each model and averages them. Then we trained a stacking classifier which basically models the output of all our chosen models using a meta model we designated.

Voting¶

Stacking¶

from sklearn.ensemble import StackingClassifier

meta_model = Pipeline([
    ('LogisticRegression', LogisticRegression(random_state=42))
])

stacking_models = {
    "DecisionTree": DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42),
    "RandomForest": RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42),
}

10
11
stacking_estimators = [
    (name, Pipeline([
        ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
        ('model', pipeline)
    ]))
    for name, pipeline in stacking_models.items()
]
stacking_clf = StackingClassifier(
    estimators=stacking_estimators,
    final_estimator=meta_model
)

best_models = {
    #"SVC": SVC(probability=True, random_state=42), #excluding due to a lack of processing resources required to process this model
    "LogisticRegression": LogisticRegression(random_state=42),
    "DecisionTree": DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42),
    "RandomForest": RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42),
    "GradientBoosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42),
    "XGBoosting": XGBClassifier(random_state=42),
    "LightGradientBoosting": LGBMClassifier(random_state=42)
}

categorical_features = X_train_reduced.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns.tolist()
numerical_features = X_train_reduced.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns.tolist()

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('target_encoder', TargetEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))
])

numerical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')),
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

voting_preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numerical_transformer, numerical_features),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
    ]
)

voting_pipelines = {}
for model_name, model in models.items():
    voting_pipelines[model_name] = Pipeline(steps=[
        ('preprocessor', voting_preprocessor),
        ('model', model)
    ])

voting_estimators = [
    (name, Pipeline([
        ('preprocessor', voting_preprocessor),
        ('model', pipeline)
    ]))
    for name, pipeline in best_models.items()
]
In [ ]:
1
voting_clf = VotingClassifier(estimators=voting_estimators, voting='soft')

from sklearn.ensemble import StackingClassifier

meta_model = Pipeline([
    ('LogisticRegression', LogisticRegression(random_state=42))
])

stacking_models = {
    "DecisionTree": DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42),
    "RandomForest": RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42),
}
In [ ]:
1
2

4
5
6
stacking_preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numerical_transformer, numerical_features),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
    ]
)
In [ ]:

11
stacking_estimators = [
    (name, Pipeline([
        ('preprocessor', stacking_preprocessor),
        ('model', pipeline)
    ]))
    for name, pipeline in stacking_models.items()
]
stacking_clf = StackingClassifier(
    estimators=stacking_estimators,
    final_estimator=meta_model
)

3.4.10 SVC model with PCA features using 20% of the training data¶

We added in Support Vector Machines Classifier since it requires few resources given our reduced feature set and we used 20% of the training data to see the extent to which it was worth it to run it on the full training data. However, the results of the reduced SVC did not lead to signficant gains in performance.

3.4.11 Hyperparamter Tuning with Best Performant Model¶

Below, we give a brief description of the models we tested along with descriptions of common hyperparameters we used for tuning each model.

Logistic Regression: Logistic regression (also known as logit regression, maximum-entropy classification (MaxEnt) or the log-linear classifier) is a supervised learning algorithm, implemented as a linear model, used for binary and multiclass classification. It models the probability of a target variable belonging to a class by using a logistic (sigmoid) function. The algorithm works by finding the best-fitting hyperplane that separates the data points of different classes in the feature space. Supported regularization hyperparameters include L1 (Lasso), L2 (Ridge) and Elastic-Net regularization to prevent overfitting and improve generalization.

[Hyperparameters:](https://scikit-learn.org/dev/modules/linear_model.html)

  • Penalty: Specifies the type of regularization to be applied.
    • Default = "l2"
    • Options = {"l1", "l2", "elasticnet", "none"}
  • C: Inverse of regularization strength (smaller values specify stronger regularization).
    • Default = 1.0, Range = (0, inf)
  • Solver: Algorithm to be used for optimization.
    • Default = "lbfgs"
    • Options = {"newton-cg", "lbfgs", "liblinear", "sag", "saga"}
  • Max_iter: Maximum number of iterations taken for the solvers to converge.
    • Default = 100, Range = [10, inf)
  • Multi_class: Handles multiclass classification.
    • Default = "auto"
    • Options = {"auto", "ovr", "multinomial"}

Support Vector Machines (SVM - Classifier): Support vector machines (SVMs) are a set of supervised learning methods used for classification, regression and outlier detection. These work by finding the hyperplane that maximizes the margin (distance) between classes in a high-dimensional space. SVMs can handle both linear and non-linear classification tasks by utilizing kernel functions. SVC, NuSVC and LinearSVC are classes capable of performing binary and multi-class classification on a dataset. SVC and NuSVC are similar methods, but accept slightly different sets of parameters and have different mathematical formulations. On the other hand, LinearSVC is another (faster) implementation of Support Vector Classification for the case of a linear kernel. We will use SVC for our work.

[Hyperparameters:](https://scikit-learn.org/dev/modules/svm.html)

  • C: Regularization parameter that controls the trade-off between maximizing the margin and minimizing classification error.
    • Default = 1.0, Range = (0, inf)
  • Kernel: Specifies the kernel type to be used in the algorithm.
    • Default = "rbf"
    • Options = {"linear", "poly", "rbf", "sigmoid", "precomputed"}
  • Degree: Degree of the polynomial kernel function (ignored by other kernels).
    • Default = 3, Range = [1, inf)
  • Gamma: Defines the influence of a single training example.
    • Default = "scale"
    • Options = {"scale", "auto"} or float
  • Class_weight: adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies for handling imbalanced datasets.
    • Default = None
    • Options = {None, "balanced", {custom dictionary}}
  • Max_iter: Maximum number of iterations in the solver.
    • Default = -1 (no limit)

Decision Tree Classifier: Decision trees are supervised learning models used for classification and regression. The tree is structured with a root node (first node with the entire dataset that all other nodes originate from), decision node (node where a choice is made), leaf nodes (final classification). Each node splits the data into subsets based on a feature from the data to lead to a final predictive outcome.

[Hyperparameters:](https://scikit-learn.org/dev/modules/generated/sklearn.tree.DecisionTreeClassifier.html)

  • Max_depth: maximum depth of the tree.
    • Default = None
  • Min_samples_split: minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
    • Default = 2
  • Min_samples_leaf: minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node.
    • Default = 1

Random Forest Classifier: Random forest classifier combines multiple decision tree classifiers on subsets of data. The prediction made from a random forest classifier is based on the classification predicted by most of the individual trees.

[Hyperparameters:](https://scikit-learn.org/1.5/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.html)

  • N_estimators: Number of trees.
    • Default = 100
  • Max_depth: maximum depth of the tree.
    • Default = None
  • Min_samples_split: minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
    • Default = 2
  • Min_samples_leaf: minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node.
    • Default = 1
  • Max_features: number of features considered when looking for best split.
    • Default = "sqrt"

Gradient Boosting (GBM, XGBM, and LightGBM): Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM) combines weak learning (i.e., models that perform slightly better than chance) decision tree models to create a stronger model. The process is iterative, so later models are built considering mistakes made by earlier models to minimize them. Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBM) is related to GBM, but XGBM improves upon GBM using parallel processing to increase speed. XGBM also includes regularization hyperparameters that can help with overfitting. Light Gradient Boosting Machine (LightGBM) is another related algorithm that is fast and efficient for large datasets. LightGBM bins data using histograms to use less memory and train faster than GBM.

Gradient Boosting:

[Hyperparameters:](https://scikit-learn.org/dev/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.GradientBoostingClassifier.html)

  • Learning_rate: shrinks the contribution of each tree.
    • Default = 0.1
  • N_estimators: number of boosting stages to perform. Larger number usually performs better.
    • Default = 100, must be in range [1, inf]
  • Max_depth: maximum depth of the individual regression estimators. Limits the number of nodes in the tree. Best value depends on the interaction of the input variables.
    • Default = 3, must be in range [1, inf) or None
  • Subsample: fraction of samples to be used for fitting the individual base learners.
    • Default = 1.0, smaller than 1 leads to reduction of variance and increase in bias. Range (0.0, 1.0]
  • Min_samples_split: Minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
    • Default = 2

Extreme Gradient Boosting:

[Hyperparameters:](https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/parameter.html)

  • Learning_rate: step size shrinkage used in update to prevent overfitting.
    • Default = 0.3, range [0, 1]
  • N_estimators: number of boosting iterations.
    • Default = 100
  • Max_depth: maximum depth of a tree. Higher values mean a more complex model that is more likely to overfit.
    • Default = 6, range [0, inf]
  • Subsample: subsample ratio of the training instances.
    • Default = 1, range (0, 1]
  • Colsample_bytree: subsample ratio of columns when constructing each tree.
    • Default = 1

Light Gradient Boosting:

[Hyperparameters:](https://lightgbm.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Parameters.html)

  • Num_leaves: Parameter to control complexity of model.
    • Default = 31, value should be smaller than 2^(max_depth)
  • Learning_rate: Shrinkage rate.
    • Default = 0.1
  • N_estimators: Number of boosting iterations.
    • Default = 100
  • Min_data_in_leaf: Minimal number of data in one leaf. This parameter can help deal with overfitting.
    • Default = 20
  • Max_depth: Limit the max depth for the model.
    • Default = -1 (no limit)

Ultimately, we decided to focus our hyper parameter tuning on our best performing model: XGBoost.

categorical_features = X_train_reduced.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns.tolist()
numerical_features = X_train_reduced.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns.tolist()

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('target_encoder', TargetEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))
])

numerical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')),
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numerical_transformer, numerical_features),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
    ]
)

pipelines = []
for model_name, model_info in models_PCA_tuning.items():
    pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
        ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
        ('model', model_info['model'])
    ])

    param_grid = {}
    for param_name, param_values in model_info['params'].items():
        param_grid[f"model__{param_name}"] = param_values

    grid_search = GridSearchCV(
        estimator=pipeline,
        param_grid=param_grid,
        cv=3,
        scoring='accuracy',
        n_jobs=-1,
    )

    pipelines.append((model_name, grid_search))

    best_models_PCA_tuning[model_name] = grid_search.best_estimator_

                    f1_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test_reduced)),
                    log_loss(y_train, model.predict_proba(X_train_reduced)[:, 1]),
                    log_loss(y_valid, model.predict_proba(X_valid_reduced)[:, 1]),
                    log_loss(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test_reduced)[:, 1])],

        4))

from math import pi

# Select a subset of top-performing models based on Test_Accuracy (you can choose other metrics as well)
top_models = expLog.nlargest(12, "Test_Accuracy")  # Adjust the number as needed
categories = ["Test_Accuracy", "Test_ROC_AUC", "Test_F1"]
values = top_models[categories].values
experiment_names = top_models["Experiment_Name"].values

# Normalize values to [0, 1] range
normalized_values = (values - values.min(axis=0)) / (values.max(axis=0) - values.min(axis=0))

# Create the radar plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8), subplot_kw={"polar": True})

# Number of variables
num_vars = len(categories)
angles = [n / float(num_vars) * 2 * pi for n in range(num_vars)]
angles += angles[:1]  # Close the circle

# Set a colormap for better aesthetics
colors = plt.cm.get_cmap("tab10", len(experiment_names))

# Plot for each model
for i, (model_values, label) in enumerate(zip(normalized_values, experiment_names)):
    data = list(model_values) + list(model_values[:1])  # Close the circle
    ax.plot(angles, data, label=label, color=colors(i))
    ax.fill(angles, data, alpha=0.1, color=colors(i))

# Add labels
ax.set_yticks([])
ax.set_xticks(angles[:-1])
ax.set_xticklabels(categories, fontsize=12)
plt.title("Radar Plot of Model Performance Metrics", fontsize=14, pad=20)

# Move the legend outside the plot
plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), fontsize=8, title="Models")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

For our modeling pipeline, we started by consolidating data from diverse sources into a single dataset and engineered features based on EDA and business understanding. We transformed categorical and numerical features, then reduced the data to 20 features using PCA, feature importance from decision trees and random forests, and correlation analysis. We tested both the complete and reduced feature sets using models like Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Decision Trees, Gradient Boosting, Extreme Gradient Boosting, and Light Gradient Boosting. Finally, we applied ensemble methods, including stacking and voting, and performed hyperparameter tuning to optimize the best-performing model. XGBoost was selected for its high accuracy (91.59%), efficiency, and scalability. However, it struggled with severe class imbalance, evident in its low recall of 0.94% and poor F1-scores for the minority class, as shown in the confusion matrix.

3.5 Deep Learning Implementation: Multi-layer perception (MLP) model in PyTorch for loan default classification in PyTorch Lighting¶

3.5.1 Initial MLP test¶

In our initial experiment, we trained a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) using PyTorch Lightning. The model architecture consisted of two hidden layers with 64 and 32 units, respectively, each followed by ReLU activation. The output layer was designed for binary classification. We used a pipeline-based preprocessing strategy to standardize numerical features and encode categorical variables before training.

The experiment was conducted on a data split, including training, validation, and test datasets. A dynamic LightningDataModule handled data loading, ensuring scalability and reproducibility. For training, we employed the Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 0.001 and monitored the validation accuracy to save the best-performing model via a checkpoint callback.

The model was trained over 20 epochs using an appropriate batch size (64). The training process utilized GPU acceleration to improve computational efficiency. Post-training, the best model checkpoint was reloaded and evaluated on the test set, achieving competitive results.

TensorBoard was used to monitor training metrics, providing insights into the models learning process.

import pytorch_lightning as pl
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
from torchmetrics import Accuracy
from torchmetrics.functional import precision, recall, f1_score, auroc
from pkg_resources import parse_version
from torchmetrics import __version__ as torchmetrics_version

class MultiLayerPerceptron(pl.LightningModule):
    def __init__(self, input_dim, hidden_units=(64, 32)):
        super().__init__()

        # Define accuracy metrics based on PyTorch Lightning version
        if parse_version(torchmetrics_version) > parse_version("0.8"):
            self.train_acc = Accuracy(task="multiclass", num_classes=2)  # Adjust num_classes
            self.valid_acc = Accuracy(task="multiclass", num_classes=2)
            self.test_acc = Accuracy(task="multiclass", num_classes=2)
        else:
            self.train_acc = Accuracy()
            self.valid_acc = Accuracy()
            self.test_acc = Accuracy()

        # Define MLP architecture
        all_layers = [nn.Flatten()]
        for hidden_unit in hidden_units:
            all_layers.append(nn.Linear(input_dim, hidden_unit))
            all_layers.append(nn.ReLU())
            input_dim = hidden_unit
        all_layers.append(nn.Linear(hidden_units[-1], 2))  # Output layer for binary classification
        self.model = nn.Sequential(*all_layers)

    def forward(self, x):
        return self.model(x)

    def training_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
        x, y = batch
        logits = self(x)
        loss = nn.functional.cross_entropy(logits, y)
        preds = torch.argmax(logits, dim=1)
        self.train_acc.update(preds, y)
        self.log("train_loss", loss, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("train_acc", self.train_acc.compute(), prog_bar=True)  # Log train accuracy

        train_precision = precision(preds, y, task="binary")
        train_recall = recall(preds, y, task="binary")
        train_f1 = f1_score(preds, y, task="binary")
        train_roc_auc = auroc(logits.softmax(dim=-1)[:, 1], y, task="binary")
        self.log("train_precision", train_precision, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("train_recall", train_recall, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("train_f1", train_f1, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("train_roc_auc", train_roc_auc, prog_bar=True)

        return loss

    def validation_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
        x, y = batch
        logits = self(x)
        loss = nn.functional.cross_entropy(logits, y)
        preds = torch.argmax(logits, dim=1)
        self.valid_acc.update(preds, y)
        self.log("valid_loss", loss, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("valid_acc", self.valid_acc.compute(), prog_bar=True)  # Log validation accuracy

        valid_precision = precision(preds, y, task="binary")
        valid_recall = recall(preds, y, task="binary")
        valid_f1 = f1_score(preds, y, task="binary")
        valid_roc_auc = auroc(logits.softmax(dim=-1)[:, 1], y, task="binary")
        self.log("valid_precision", valid_precision, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("valid_recall", valid_recall, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("valid_f1", valid_f1, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("valid_roc_auc", valid_roc_auc, prog_bar=True)

        return loss

    def test_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
        x, y = batch
        logits = self(x)
        loss = nn.functional.cross_entropy(logits, y)
        preds = torch.argmax(logits, dim=1)
        self.test_acc.update(preds, y)
        self.log("test_loss", loss, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("test_acc", self.test_acc.compute(), prog_bar=True)  # Log test accuracy

        test_precision = precision(preds, y, task="binary")
        test_recall = recall(preds, y, task="binary")
        test_f1 = f1_score(preds, y, task="binary")
        test_roc_auc = auroc(logits.softmax(dim=-1)[:, 1], y, task="binary")
        self.log("test_precision", test_precision, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("test_recall", test_recall, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("test_f1", test_f1, prog_bar=True)
        self.log("test_roc_auc", test_roc_auc, prog_bar=True)


        return loss

    def configure_optimizers(self):
        return torch.optim.Adam(self.parameters(), lr=0.001)

from torch.utils.data import DataLoader, TensorDataset, random_split

#TODO: make sure this data has been scaled in the preprocessor that generated it
# from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
# scaler = StandardScaler()
# X_train_reduced = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(X_train_reduced), columns=X_train_reduced.columns)
# X_test_reduced = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(X_test_reduced), columns=X_test_reduced.columns)

# Convert your train/test data into PyTorch tensors
X_train_tensor = torch.tensor(X_train_reduced.values, dtype=torch.float32)
y_train_tensor = torch.tensor(y_train.values, dtype=torch.long)
X_test_tensor = torch.tensor(X_test_reduced.values, dtype=torch.float32)

y_test_tensor = torch.tensor(y_test.values, dtype=torch.long)

# Create datasets

train_size = int(0.8 * len(dataset))
val_size = len(dataset) - train_size
train_dataset, val_dataset = random_split(dataset, [train_size, val_size])
test_dataset = TensorDataset(X_test_tensor, y_test_tensor)

# Create dataloaders
batch_size = 64
train_loader = DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)
val_loader = DataLoader(val_dataset, batch_size=batch_size)
test_loader = DataLoader(test_dataset, batch_size=batch_size)

class CustomDataModule(pl.LightningDataModule):
    def __init__(self, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, batch_size=64):
        super().__init__()
        self.X_train = X_train
        self.X_test = X_test
        self.y_train = y_train
        self.y_test = y_test
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.input_dim = X_train.shape[1]  # Automatically determine input_dim

    def setup(self, stage=None):
        # Split training data into training and validation sets
        dataset = TensorDataset(torch.tensor(self.X_train.values, dtype=torch.float32),
                                 torch.tensor(self.y_train.values, dtype=torch.long))
        train_size = int(0.8 * len(dataset))
        val_size = len(dataset) - train_size
        self.train_dataset, self.val_dataset = random_split(dataset, [train_size, val_size])

        # Prepare test dataset
        self.test_dataset = TensorDataset(torch.tensor(self.X_test.values, dtype=torch.float32),
                                          torch.tensor(self.y_test.values, dtype=torch.long))

    def train_dataloader(self):
        return DataLoader(self.train_dataset, batch_size=self.batch_size, shuffle=True)

    def val_dataloader(self):
        return DataLoader(self.val_dataset, batch_size=self.batch_size)

    def test_dataloader(self):
        return DataLoader(self.test_dataset, batch_size=self.batch_size)

from pytorch_lightning.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint

# Initialize the model
input_dim = data_module.input_dim  # Dynamically fetched from the DataModule
mlp_model = MultiLayerPerceptron(input_dim=input_dim, hidden_units=(64, 32))

# Define callbacks
checkpoint_callback = ModelCheckpoint(
    monitor="valid_acc", mode="max", save_top_k=1, verbose=True
)


# Define trainer
trainer = pl.Trainer(
    max_epochs=20,
    callbacks=[checkpoint_callback],
    accelerator="gpu" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu",
    devices=1 if torch.cuda.is_available() else None,
)


# Train the model
trainer.fit(mlp_model, datamodule=data_module)

3.5.2 Exploring Neural Network Architectures¶

To evaluate performance, we tested four Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) architectures:

  • Sparse Input MLP: A lightweight baseline with fewer neurons to benchmark performance against more complex models.
  • Simple Deep MLP: Added depth (128, 64, 32 units) to capture complex patterns in the data.
  • MLP with Dropout: Incorporated dropout (rate = 0.2) to mitigate overfitting, improving generalization.
  • Wider MLP: Increased width (512, 256, 128 units) for greater representational power.

Results were systematically logged to compare accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC, guiding architectural decisions.

def run_experiment(model_name, hidden_units, dropout_rate=None):
    # Modify the architecture based on the experiment
    if dropout_rate:
        class DropoutMLP(MultiLayerPerceptron):
            def __init__(self, input_dim, hidden_units, dropout_rate):
                super().__init__(input_dim, hidden_units)
                layers = []
                for hidden_unit in hidden_units:
                    layers.append(nn.Linear(input_dim, hidden_unit))
                    layers.append(nn.ReLU())
                    layers.append(nn.Dropout(p=dropout_rate))
                    input_dim = hidden_unit
                layers.append(nn.Linear(hidden_units[-1], 2))  # Output layer
                self.model = nn.Sequential(*layers)
        model = DropoutMLP(input_dim=data_module.input_dim, hidden_units=hidden_units, dropout_rate=dropout_rate)
    else:
        model = MultiLayerPerceptron(input_dim=data_module.input_dim, hidden_units=hidden_units)

    # Train and test the model
    trainer = pl.Trainer(
        max_epochs=20,
        callbacks=[checkpoint_callback],
        accelerator="gpu" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu",
        devices=1 if torch.cuda.is_available() else None,
    )
    trainer.fit(model, datamodule=data_module)
    results = trainer.test(model=model, dataloaders=data_module.test_dataloader(), verbose=False)

    # Log metrics
    metrics = {
        "Experiment_Name": model_name,
        "Hidden_Units": hidden_units,
        "Dropout_Rate": dropout_rate,
        "Test_Accuracy": results[0]["test_acc"],
        "Test_Loss": results[0]["test_loss"],
        "Test_Precision": results[0]["test_precision"],
        "Test_Recall": results[0]["test_recall"],
        "Test_ROC_AUC": results[0]["test_roc_auc"],
        "Test_F1": results[0]["test_f1"],
    }
    experiment_logs.append(metrics)
    print(f"Experiment {model_name} complete!")

# Melt the DataFrame to reshape it for grouped bar plotting
melted_logs = experiment_logs_df.melt(
    id_vars="Experiment_Name",
    value_vars=["Test_Accuracy", "Test_Precision", "Test_Recall", "Test_F1", "Test_ROC_AUC"],
    var_name="Metric",
    value_name="Value"
)

# Plot the metrics
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.barplot(
    data=melted_logs,
    x="Experiment_Name",
    y="Value",
    hue="Metric",
    palette="viridis"
)
plt.title("Comparison of Metrics Across Experiments")
plt.xlabel("Experiment")
plt.ylabel("Metric Value")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(title="Metric", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc="upper left")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

mlp_metrics = experiment_logs_df[["Experiment_Name", "Test_ROC_AUC", "Test_Accuracy"]]
non_mlp_metrics = expLog[["Experiment_Name", "Test_ROC_AUC", "Test_Accuracy"]]

combined_df = pd.concat([mlp_metrics, non_mlp_metrics], ignore_index=True)

metrics_to_plot = ["Test_ROC_AUC", "Test_Accuracy"]


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))


x = np.arange(len(combined_df["Experiment_Name"]))

width = 0.35

for i, metric in enumerate(metrics_to_plot):
    ax.bar(x + i * width, combined_df[metric], width, label=metric)

ax.set_xlabel("Models", fontsize=12)
ax.set_ylabel("Scores", fontsize=12)
ax.set_title("Key Metrics Comparison Across Models", fontsize=14)
ax.set_xticks(x + width / 2)
ax.set_xticklabels(combined_df["Experiment_Name"], rotation=45, ha="right")
ax.legend(title="Metric", fontsize=10)
ax.grid(axis="y", linestyle="--", alpha=0.7)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
